default 
defaultThe December 1994 
defaultSACTRA
default report
default 
default ‘Trunk Roads and the Generation of Traffic’ 
defaultis probably the most robust evidence and analysis of all this.
default&#xa0;
default 
defaultThe SACTRA work itself pulled on a number of different evidence sources - not only the before-and-after traffic counts but also inferences from la
defaultrge numbers of studies of values of time, demand elasticities, differential growth rates, and surveys. It was because all these told a broadly consistent story that SACTRA felt able to be more decisive in its conclusions than the DTp was expecting at the t
defaultime. 
defaultSince then there has been one completely different type of evidence base as well: this is the complementary literature on traffic reduction following road space reductions (pedestrianisation, bus lanes, disasters, maintenance closures, etc). This is
default important in its own right, but also significant in giving confidence that the induced traffic effect is not an artefact due to economic growth or similar. The largest empirical compilation is a book Cairns S, Hass-Klau C and Goodwin P (1998) Traffic Effe
defaultct of Highway Capacity Reductions, Landor Publishing, London, with some updating papers subsequently of which one was awarded a gold medal by the Institution of Civil Engineers.
defaultSACTRA does show that the net effect of road enlargements could actually creat
defaulte more congestion.
default&#xa0;
default Mogridge and Thompson really propounded this 
defaultin their various books and papers 
defaultand it certainly can apply most in big cities on radial routes. 
default&#xa0;
defaultExplained simply there is a vic
defaulti
defaultous circle --- more road space – more car use - 
default&#xa0;
defaultless public
default transport use – fares go up, frequency goes down – more people transfer to cars etc and the new equilibrium point is a lower level of service in both cars and Public Transport.
default&#xa0;
