defaultIt appears that 
defaultthe statements of certain business people and the roads lobby
default is being used to make the case for Trunk road improvements rather than any evidence.  I
defaultt is an easy message to say that widening 
defaulta road would appear to be a solution to congestion! The real message on transport policy is much more complicated.
defaultPhil Goodwin’s article in LTTdefaultInduced traffic again. And again. And again.defaultPhil GoodwindefaultWhen the costs of travel are reduced, people do more 
defaultof it. When the costs of car travel are reduced, people use cars more. Why are these obvious propositions so forgettable that they need to be proved anew every decade?
defaultIt was way back in 1925 that the opening of a new section on the Great West Road demonst
defaultrated 'the remarkable manner in which new roads generate new traffic', as Bressey wrote in 1937.  Soon forgotten. Glanville and Smeed at the Road Research Laboratory rediscovered it in 1958, and Foster, at Oxford, in 1963, and it was remembered long enough
default to appear in Ministry of Transport advice in 1968, which said:
default"Generated traffic on large schemes has often amounted to between 5% and 25% over and above the normal forecast traffic level…larger in exceptional cases"
defaultWithin three years the advice disappeared (nobody ever said why), and generated traffic was routinely not calculated for road schemes. The DoT took a legal case to the House of Lords to prevent such forecasts being challenged by objectors. But the evidence
default kept re-appearing: a GLC study demonstrated it empirically in 1985, as did Martin Mogridge and his colleagues in 1987, and it was sharply reinforced in 1988 after the M25 exceeded its long term forecast traffic growth within months of opening. 
defaultIn 1994 SA
defaultCTRA, the Standing Advisory Committee on Trunk Road Assessment, published its best known report, on what it renamed 'induced' traffic. The average traffic flow on 151 improved roads was 10.4% higher than forecasts which omitted induced traffic, and  16.4% 
defaulthigher than forecast on 85 alternative routes that improvements had been intended to relieve. In a dozen more detailed case studies the measured increase in traffic ranged from 9% to 44% in the short run, and 20% to 178% in the longer run.  This fitted in 
defaultwith other evidence on elasticities, and aggregate data. The conclusion was 
default"an average road improvement, for which traffic growth due to all other factors is forecast correctly, will see an additional [ie induced] 10% of base traffic in the short term an
defaultd 20% in the long term"
defaultThe Department of Transport accepted this. The report was updated it in a special issue of 'Transportation' in 1996 (including my own review, as lead author of the 'evidence' chapters 
defaultof the SACTRA report).  Bob Noland and others fo
defaultr the USA, and many authors in Europe, have since demonstrated similar international results.
defaultFast forward to July this year. CPRE published a report by Lilli Matson, Lynn Sloman, Ian Taylor, and John Elliott. The authors were known to me - I worked with L
defaultilli on the Ten Year Plan for Transport, with a report we called 'Running to Stand Still'; with Lynn on 'Smarter Choices', and also the West Midlands TIF programme; and with John (who did the original 1985 GLC study, with Jill Beardwood and Steve Purnell) 
defaulton the Thames Gateway Bridge.  They are a serious group of engaged professionals, and I opened their report with interest.
defaultIt's called 'Beyond Transport Infrastructure', and what they have done is look in detail at three big schemes on the A27, A34 and M65
default, and a further ten schemes on the A5, A6, A41, A43, A46, A66, A500 and A1033. These were schemes undertaken 
defaultafterdefault SACTRA's 1994 report had been finished and accepted. They reported:
default"Careful scrutiny of the traffic flow data suggests that traffic growth a
defaultfter the scheme opened has been significantly higher than growth on other nearby road corridors or national traffic growth"
default"…in all three case studies the current traffic flows are near or already in excess of what was predicted for 2010. In towns with by
defaultpasses, such as Newbury and Polegate, the new roads did significantly reduce the town centre traffic levels. However, these reductions are not as great as originally forecast and there has subsequently been regrowth in traffic levels on the bypassed roads.
default The net effect in combination with the new road is generally a considerable overall increase in traffic".
defaultTheir final conclusion is remarkably restrained. After noting the Highways Agency's own explanations for the extra traffic growth, (which were intrig
defaultuingly similar to those rejected by SACTRA 12 years earlier), they write 
default"Nevertheless, in view of the fact that many of the schemes reviewed have demonstrated significant increases in traffic volumes (in the range of 10-35%, within a period of one to two
default years after opening), there would seem a strong case to consider the issue of induced traffic in more detail in future evaluations".
defaultSo 1925, 1937, 1958, 1963, 1968, 1985, 1987, 1988, 1994, 1996, now 2006: for eighty years, every eight years on average th
defaultere has been the same experience, the same conclusions - even, for goodness sake, more or less the same figures. The evidence has been consistent,  recurrent, unchallenged by serious countervailing evidence, but repeatedly forgotten. CPRE have done us a se
defaultrvice, I think, but really it should just not have been possible for them to find, 12 years after SACTRA, the same mistakes.
defaultThere may well be situations when it is justified to encourage more traffic, but this should be done cautiously, with eyes wide ope
defaultn about the implications, not by denial. Induced traffic tends to increase environmental damage, and usually tends to reduce the calculated benefit-cost ratio of a road improvement, because the period of relief from congestion will be shorter than planned;
default also because the benefit to the marginal extra travellers is less; and because assuming the extra traffic is not induced artificially makes the 'without' case worse than it really would be. It is a bit more complicated to predict.
defaultMaybe that's the problem
default. The methods you can use if there is no induced traffic are cheaper, and have the incidental side effect of uplifting the calculated benefit. If the promoter of a scheme is the same agency as is responsible for its appraisal, that's two quite big incentiv
defaultes to get it wrong, and no countervailing pressure to get it right. Except, perhaps, the embarrassment of the next research study? But that will be nearly a decade later, and somebody else's problem. 
